Please refer further to =E2=80=98ANZ1789 Response to building consent conce=
rns=E2=80=99 & 39775 23 Mays Street, Devonport Post Fire Structural Assessm=
ent REV B , May 26 [Attached]


6.2.4 =E2=80=93 Wall insulation [ground floor external]

Acknowledging that wall insulation remains in places to the ground floor ex=
ternal walls. Further to this, it is acknowledged that the wall insulation =
to the external ground floor wall framing will be included in the scope of =
work.
As this thermal insulation is acknowledged as being pre-existing with the d=
welling =E2=80=93 it is eligible to be replaced under Schedule 1 of the Bui=
lding Act, 2004.

Please refer to =E2=80=98ANZ1789 Response to building consent concerns=E2=
=80=99 [Attached]


6.2.5 =E2=80=93 Unreinforced masonry perimeter load bearing structural walls

These wall present with smoke staining to a variety of degrees depending on=
 the locations within the ground floor of the dwelling. Tower has acknowled=
ged this and has provided a response to this in the letter to Wyn Williams =
dated 27 March, 2026. As below:

Masonry Walls


  1.  Prendos raises a possibility of heat=E2=80=91related weakening of unr=
einforced masonry walls. Tower has not been provided with any evidence that=
 the masonry foundation wall has been structurally compromised by the fire.=
 The masonry shows no visible fire damage beyond minimal smoke staining. Th=
e limited charring observed to adjacent timber framing indicates temperatur=
es well below those at which clay brick masonry would be structurally affec=
ted.


  1.  On that basis, Tower considers the masonry walls to be materially una=
ffected. If your client wishes to obtain independent expert evidence demons=
trating heat=E2=80=91related damage, Tower will consider that material if p=
rovided. If your client provides a report that materially changes Tower=E2=
=80=99s position on this, then we would consider reimbursement of the reaso=
nable costs associated with this.

Tower has now provided a specific CPeng report to support our prior asserti=
on above. Please refer further to =E2=80=98ANZ1789 Response to building con=
sent concerns=E2=80=99 & 39775 23 Mays Street, Devonport Post Fire Structur=
al Assessment REV B , May 26 [Attached]


6.2.6 =E2=80=93 Fire damaged rear deck structure

Deck height of over 1.5m is irrelevant as Schedule 1 applies because we are=
 replacing damaged components of an existing structure with same materials.=
 Referred to in letter to Wyn Williams dated 27 March,  4(d)
Please refer to =E2=80=98ANZ1789 Response to building consent concerns=E2=
=80=99 [Attached]


6.2.7 =E2=80=93 Fire damage observed to timber framing and fixings below su=
nroom

All hardwood decking to the sunroom is scheduled to be replaced, as schedul=
ed in line 336 of the scope of works.
All fixings can be inspected once flooring above has been removed. Noting t=
hat these fixings are all stainless steel =E2=80=93 which will respond to c=
leaning to remove surface smoke residue.
Items such as stainless-steel joist-hangers can be included in the scope of=
 works to be replaced if acceptable cleanings is not achieved.
Any timber framing within the subfloor area of the sunroom will respond to =
light surface cleaning, as the resulting damage to this framing is negligea=
ble smoke damage.


6.2.8 =E2=80=93 Roof space fire damage

On 21 August 2025 Grant Metson [ Tower Insurance ] & Lei Yui [ ASURNZ ] ent=
ered the roof space to conduct a thorough investigation of the roof space. =
As did Alexandra Dalzell [Forensic Specialists] to complete forensic testin=
g for contamination.
The findings of the Forensic Testing where that minor trace elements of smo=
ke contamination were present to the underside of the roofing underlay pape=
r directly above the external wall cavities. Whilst no physical evidence of=
 any smoke damage was visible to any of the elements within the roof space =
=E2=80=93 there was a marginally perceptible odour of smoke in the roof spa=
ce. To that end the following has been provided for within the scope of wor=
ks:


  *   Replacement of 94.53 sqm of R3.2 170mm ceiling insulation to the roof=
 space. Total replacement. Line 101 of the scope of works.
  *   Cleaning and smoke sealing of the complete roof structure framing. Li=
ne 75 of the scope of works.
  *   Complete replacement of the roofing iron underlay. Line 53 of the sco=
pe of works.
  *   Complete replacement of the corrugated roofing cladding. Line 74 of t=
he scope of works.
  *   Scaffolding and shrink-wrap enclosure of the dwelling to facilitate t=
he above works. Line 17 & 18 of the scope of works.

None of the work proposed above require a building consent as they fall wit=
hin the requirements of Schedule 1 of the building Act, 2004.


Prendos Report =E2=80=93 Section 7.0 =E2=80=93 Analysis

7.1.1

Braced walls
Bracing walls identified will be re-lined with gib wall linings in accordan=
ce with NZS3604 under Schedule 1 of the building Act, 2004.
Wall insulation to external ground floor walls
Wall insulation to the external walls of the ground floor of the dwelling w=
ill be replaced were the same has been removed or has been affected by the =
fire. This will be included in a revised scope of works to be shared by all=
 parties.


7.2 =E2=80=93 Requirement of Building Consent

7.2.1 through to 7.2.3 [including incorrectly formatted 7.2.4]

Tower Insurance re-iterates its position that all works proposed in the sco=
pe of works are permissible under schedule 1 of the building Act, 2004. All=
 points raised in the Prendos report : 7.2.1 through to 7.2.3 [including in=
correctly formatted 7.2.4] are incorrect based on the following:

