7.3 =E2=80=93 Owners Obligations

7.3.1 and 7.3.2
Relates to recurring point of contention regarding the correct application =
of Schedule 1 of the Building Act, 2004.
Please refer to =E2=80=98ANZ1789 Response to building consent concerns=E2=
=80=99 [Attached]

7.3.3

Refer to response provided in letter to Wyn Williams dated 27 March, 2026. =
As follows:

Policy Standard

11. The applicable standard for reinstatement is governed by the express te=
rms of the Policy. It is not determined by trade terminology used in a scop=
e of works, nor by subjective expectations as to aesthetic outcome.

12. Under the Policy, Tower=E2=80=99s obligation in the event of an economi=
c repair is to meet the reasonable cost of repairing the house to a standar=
d that is reasonably equivalent to its appearance, size, functionality, and=
 relative quality when new, without necessarily reproducing it exactly. Tha=
t formulation reflects a well-established distinction in New Zealand insura=
nce law between a requirement to restore functional and qualitative equival=
ence, and any obligation to deliver a pristine or upgraded outcome.

13. Where damage is repaired rather than replaced in full, the Policy recog=
nises that the repaired element cannot, in a literal sense, be rendered =E2=
=80=9Cnew=E2=80=9D. In those circumstances, the applicable standard is dire=
cted to the materials and workmanship used in the repair, assessed by refer=
ence to whether the completed works restore the relevant element to a condi=
tion that is reasonably equivalent in function and quality to its insured s=
tate, rather than whether the element is indistinguishable from a newly con=
structed component.

14. The Policy does not impose an obligation to improve, upgrade, or replic=
ate owner-driven renovations, nor does it require reinstatement to current =
building standards except to the extent required by law. The use of modern =
materials and methods is contemplated only as a means of achieving the requ=
ired functional equivalence, not as a basis for elevating the standard of t=
he building beyond that insured.

15. The scope prepared by Asurnz was developed to give effect to this contr=
actual standard. It reflects the assessor=E2=80=99s determination of what w=
ork is reasonably required to repair the insured damage, including replacem=
ent where necessary and cleaning, repainting, or reinstatement where replac=
ement is not required. The absence of the phrase =E2=80=9Cwhen new=E2=80=9D=
 in the scope does not alter the standard to be applied, which is fixed by =
the Policy wording itself.

16. Any assessment of the adequacy of the scope or of completed works must =
therefore be undertaken by reference to the Policy definition of repair cos=
t, and not by reference to a requirement to return repaired elements to the=
ir precise pre-loss condition or to an elevated aesthetic standard achieved=
 through prior renovations.

17. Where Tower elects to manage the repairs, the works will be carried out=
 with reasonable care and skill and in compliance with applicable legal req=
uirements. That obligation does not require the highest possible finish or =
the adoption of a particular trade standard unless expressly required by th=
e Policy or otherwise agreed.

18. Tower=E2=80=99s position remains that the proposed reinstatement works,=
 when carried out in accordance with the agreed scope, will meet the Policy=
 standard.


7.3.4 =E2=80=93 Decontamination.

All swab samples that have returned a positive result as identified in the =
ASURNZ report and Forensic Specialists Combustion Pre-Decontamination repor=
t will be retested to verify that cleaning, and or replacement of these ite=
ms has provided successful decontamination.
The Forensic Specialist report recommends:
b) Decontamination is undertaken by a suitably qualified and experienced co=
ntractor to reduce the levels of chemical and combustion particulates as fa=
r as reasonably practicable.
c) Following completion of the cleaning inside the building we recommend th=
e areas are re-tested and a Clearance Certificate issued only to the areas =
highlighted as having elevated levels.
This report is to be read in its entirety to ensure a complete understandin=
g of the surveying, sampling, and reporting process is understood.

Any items / elements which have returned positive contamination results are=
 included in the proposed scope of works to either cleaned, decontaminated =
or replaced. The contamination testing completed and remedial works propose=
d are sufficient to ensure that the policy will fulfill its obligations, wi=
th the provision of post cleaning testing verification and corresponding co=
ntamination clearance certificate .


